b"[![](../../cdshop/cdinfo.jpg)](../../cdshop/index.htm)  \n[Sacred Texts](../../index.htm)  [Hinduism](../index.htm)  [Index](index.htm)\n[Previous](sbe48114.htm)  [Next](sbe48116.htm)\n\n* * *\n\n16\\. And on account of the settled meaning.\n\nThe word 'ether,' moreover, is known to have, among\n\np. 320\n\nother meanings, that of Brahman. Compare 'For who could breathe, who could\nbreathe forth, if that ether were not bliss?' (Taitt. Up. II, 7); 'All these\nbeings take their rise from the ether' ( _Kh_. Up. I, 9, 1). It has to be kept\nin view that in the text under discussion the meaning 'Brahman' is supported\nby what is said about the qualities of the small ether--viz. freedom from sin,\n&c.--and hence is stronger than the other meaning--, according to which aka\n_s_ a signifies the elemental ether.\n\nSo far the Sutras have refuted the view of the small ether being the element.\nThey now enter on combating the notion that the small ether may possibly be\nthe individual soul.\n\n* * *\n\n[Next: 17. If it be said that on account of reference to the other one he is\nmeant; we say no...](sbe48116.htm)\n\n"